The paper deals with fundamental problems in networks, such as naming and counting, and their variations, which are typical topics in Distributed Computing (cs.DC). The networks are anonymous and dynamic, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) category. The paper also discusses the connectivity model and the worst-case adversary, which are common topics in the Distributed Systems (cs.DS) category. The paper also involves information theory, as the nodes have minimal knowledge of the network, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) category. Finally, the paper discusses the computational complexity of the problems, which may also place it in the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) category.
